  issue = {1},
  journal = {Logical Methods in Computer Science},
  title = {{A Cubical Language for Bishop Sets}},
  volume = {18},
}</meta><meta name="doi">10.46298/lmcs-18(1:43)2022</meta><meta name="venue">Logical Methods in Computer Science</meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>We present XTT, a version of Cartesian cubical type theory specialized for Bishop sets à la <link href="thierrycoquand.xml" type="local" title="Thierry Coquand">Coquand</link>, in which every type enjoys a definitional version of the uniqueness of identity proofs. Using cubical notions, XTT reconstructs many of the ideas underlying Observational Type Theory, a version of intensional type theory that supports function extensionality. We prove the canonicity property of XTT (that every closed boolean is definitionally equal to a constant) by Artin gluing.</p></mainmatter> <backmatter><contributions/> <context/> <related><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>19606</anchor> <rss>thierrycoquand.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Person</taxon> <addr>thierrycoquand</addr>  <route>thierrycoquand.xml</route>   <title>Thierry Coquand</title> <meta name="external">https://www.cse.chalmers.se/~coquand/</meta><meta name="position">Professor</meta><meta name="institution">University of Gothenburg</meta><meta name="orcid">0000-0002-5429-5153</meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter>              
            
